Hypertensive pneumothorax is more common in tall and thin
young adults (primary pneumothorax) or in patients with
chronic pulmonary diseases or chest trauma (secondary
pneumothorax). On physical examination, we expect
asymmetry in lung auscultation and the trachea may be
dislocated to the contralateral side of the pneumothorax.
Boerhaave Syndrome is more common in patients who
presented vomiting before the chest pain started, were
submitted to endoscopic procedures or had chest trauma.
